Objective

For this publication, our objective is to take a comprehensive look at the salary of Forensic Anthropologists. We want to do this two-fold. 1) Look at the factors within the FA group to see what factors influence Salary Index (salary/COI). 2) Compare Salary Index (SI) of FAs to other types of Anthropologists - Cultural, Archaeology, Linguistic(?), and other Biological. For this round of analysis, I am going to try something new - and collapse SI into categories using unsupervised K-Means Clustering. To do so, I am going to create SI range categories based on the All Academic Anthropologists dataset and apply those same categories to the FAs Only data. Therefore, I actually have to upload the All_Anthros dataset first:

1. Create SI Categories using Unsupervised K-Means Clustering

base <- read_excel('ANTH salary data 6_EYC.xlsx',sheet='All Anthros updated')
all <- base[,c(3,5,7,8,11,16)]  # select variables: Sex, Basic Classification, Position Rank, Administrative Duties, Specialty Simple, Salary Index
colnames(all) <- c('Sex','Basic_Class','Rank','Admin','Subfield','Salary_Index')  # rename columns

all$Admin[is.na(all$Admin)] <- 0
factor_cols <- c('Sex','Basic_Class','Rank','Admin','Subfield')  # identify categorical variables
all[factor_cols] <- lapply(all[factor_cols],factor)  # factor categorical variables
all$Basic_Class <- factor(all$Basic_Class, levels=c("Special Focus Four-Year","Associate's Colleges","Baccalaureate College","Master's Colleges & Universities","Doctoral Universities"))
all$Rank <- recode(all$Rank,'Adjunct'='Term','Assistant Professor'='Assistant Professor','Associate Dean and Professor'='Special Rank','Associate Professor'='Associate Professor','Associate Professor and Chair'='Associate Professor','Dean'='Special Rank','Department Head'='Special Rank','Director'='Special Rank','Distinguished Professor'='Special Rank','Distinguished Professor of Science'='Special Rank','Distinguished University Professor'='Special Rank','Instructor'='Term','Lecturer'='Term','PostDoc'='Term','President'='Special Rank','Presidents Professor'='Special Rank','President Emeritus'='Special Rank','Professor'='Full Professor','Professor and Associate Chair'='Full Professor','Provost'='Special Rank','Regents Professor'='Special Rank','VAP'='Term','Vice Provost'='Special Rank')  # Special Rank == Dean, Associate Dean, President, etc
all$Rank <- factor(all$Rank, levels=c("Term","Assistant Professor","Associate Professor","Full Professor","Special Rank"))
all <- all[-341,]  # remove same individual from FA dataset

## K-Means Clustering of Salary_Index Category
wss_vec <- NULL
set.seed(123)
for(i in 1:15){
  temp <- kmeans(all$Salary_Index, i, iter.max=25, nstart=1)
  wss_vec <- c(wss_vec, temp$tot.withinss)
}

wss_mat <- cbind(seq(1,15),wss_vec)

plot(wss_mat[,1],wss_mat[,2],pch=19,xlab='k number of clusters',ylab='Within-cluster Sum of Squares')
lines(wss_mat[,1],wss_mat[,2],type='l')

From the plot, it looks like the best number of clusters, via the elbow method, is four clusters.

RandomForest and Variable Importance

So, this is a new analysis that I figured I would try out after chatting with Kyra. RandomForest sets up multiple decision trees and provides a metric of Variable Importance for each variable. Also, we have a new dataset to play with! Yay!

Luckily, there is no danger in correlated traits with a Random Forest model, because the decision tree will take care of them by ranking one with higher importance and reducing the importance of the other variable(s) accordingly.

RFM <- fa[,c(1:3,5:9,11,12)]  ## remove Salary_Index column

## Select best mtry value
set.seed(123)
mtry <- tuneRF(RFM[,c(1:9)],RFM$SI_Cat,ntreeTry=500,stepFactor=1.5,improve=0.01,trace=TRUE,plot=FALSE)
## mtry = 3  OOB error = 54.39% 
## Searching left ...
## mtry = 2     OOB error = 54.39% 
## 0 0.01 
## Searching right ...
## mtry = 4     OOB error = 57.02% 
## -0.0483871 0.01
best.m <- mtry[mtry[,2]==min(mtry[,2]),1]
print(mtry)
##       mtry  OOBError
## 2.OOB    2 0.5438596
## 3.OOB    3 0.5438596
## 4.OOB    4 0.5701754
print(best.m)
## 2.OOB 3.OOB 
##     2     3
set.seed(123)
rf <- randomForest(SI_Cat ~., data=RFM, importance=TRUE, mtry=2, ntree=500)
print(rf)
##

## Rank                9.5162911
## Admin               2.4789907
## Active_Years       13.9150675

Classification accuracy for this model: 44.74%.. Take a look at the confusion matrix as well. We can see that Active Years, Rank, and Basic Classification are the most important variables, per the right plot and the MeanDecreaseGini coefficients. Gini coefficient measures the purity of nodes at each split (aka the homogeneity of classes). This is the measure we use when running a categorical RFM. It is interesting to note that 2 of the top 3 most important variables only relate to Academic FAs. This is probably due to the imbalance of samples, Academic vs.Applied.

Because the total number of samples for FAs only is 114, the sample isnt large enough to build the model on a training set and testing on a test set. We WILL do this for the academic anthropologist sample!

Here, the Classification Accuracy for Academic FAs only is: 41.56%. So slightly worse than the full model. Again, Active Years, Rank, and Basic Classification are the most important variables in the model. From the confusion matrix, we can see that the Low SI category is incorrectly classified 70.83% of the time, and mostly incorrectly classified as Middle class. This could indicate that there is little difference between the Low and Middle SI categories, and the only distinguishing SI category is High SI when you have enough years in the field, and have received a high enough rank.

Conclusions

When comparing the percentages of variance explained by each random forest model, it is apparent that there seems to be more distinguishible patterns to Salary Index for Academic compared to Applied forensic anthropologists, but the best RFM model did include both types of FAs.

Next, we are going to run randomForest again, to see the variable importance and look at how much variance in SI Category can be explained by our variables. This time, we will split our training and test set by 80-20.

Random Forest - All Academics

## Detection Prevalence      0.3284     0.2388      0.16418     0.2687
## Balanced Accuracy         0.8318     0.6947      0.57201     0.6233

50.37% Classification Accuracy.

So here, there are a number of additional statistics that should be addressed. The No Information Rate (NIR) shows the proportion of the largest class in the sample. Here, we see that one of our classes (Middle) makes up 50% of our sample. The p-value is for a one-way hypothesis that tests whetehr the accuracy rate is statistically significantly different than the NIR, thus indicating that the RFM is indeed performing informed classificaitons, and isnt simply performing well due to the imbalance of classes. The Kappa value also reports the overall agreement of the RFM predictions compared to the actual classifications. Since Kappa values range from 0 to 1, a Kappa of 0.5318 is actually pretty okay! The Mcnemars Test P-value test for paired symmetry in the dataset. Because we failed to reject the null hypothesis, this means that there are no statistical associations between our classes.
